## Migration Analysis

**Thread termination APIs found:**
| API | Line | Pattern |
|-----|-------|---------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption â€” wakes thread from `WaitOne` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Fallback kill after timeout â€” throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Blocking call that needs cancellation-aware replacement |

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };

        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns immediately when either the event is
            // signaled (index 0) or cancellation is requested (index 1).
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (index == 1) // cancellation
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items â€” the original code had a race
            // where rapid Enqueue calls could leave items stranded
            // because Reset() cleared the signal before they were
            // dequeued.
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();               // wakes RunLoop via WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);         // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

## Key Changes

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` | `Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Cancellation token signaling | `Interrupt()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Allows waking on **either** new work or cancellation |
| `while (true)` | `while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative exit â€” the loop must voluntarily check |
| No `IDisposable` | Implements `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed |

## Bug Fix Included

The original code had a **race condition**: rapid `Enqueue` calls could strand items. The signal was set multiple times but `Reset()` cleared it after dequeuing only one item, leaving the rest stuck until the next enqueue. The migrated version drains the entire queue each time the event fires.

## Pitfalls to Watch

1. **Cancellation is cooperative** â€” if `Handle(item)` runs for a long time, `Stop()` won't interrupt it mid-execution. If `Handle` can be long-running, pass `_cts.Token` into it and check periodically.
2. **Don't forget `Dispose`** â€” leaking `CancellationTokenSource` causes callback/timer leaks.
3. **`Join` can still time out** â€” but unlike before, you **cannot** call `Abort()` as a fallback. Design `Handle()` to respect cancellation so the thread exits promptly.
4. **`Thread.Sleep` in `Handle`** â€” if the handler sleeps, replace with `_cts.Token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so cancellation wakes it.
